Predicting Default Payments of Credit Card Clients in Taiwan


Ruobing Wang
June 8, 2019

Overview¶

In the real life, when a customer of a bank fall into financial difficulties, it usually do not happen at once.

For banks, risk management and default detection has always been a crucial part in issuing credit cards.

All in all, defaults on credit card bill payment can result in great financial loss.

In order to reduce or even prevent loss of this kind, banks need to determine appropriate given credit for each specific client based on their information. There are some indicators which we can use to expect the final outcome. Such like late payments.

In this project, we will use the data of credit card clients in Taiwan from April 2005 to September 2005 which contains information on default payments, demographic factors, credit data, history of payment, and bill statements to see:

  1. How does the probability of default payment vary by categories of different demographic variables?

  2. Which variables are the strongest predictors of default payment?

This is a really really long report. I spend a lot of time on the EDA part and try two different ways to solve problems which you can see in a second. Basically, it will do as the following sequence:

    1. Visualize the dataset and check the imbalance and missing data.
    1. Using decision tree as the first time and found we can not simply use the accuracy score. Then I use F1 score.
    1. Data cleaning and Feature engineering
    1. Sampling by using upsample, downsample and SMOTE.
    1. Training and Testing
    1. Finding the threshold and find the best f1 score
    1. Using ROC AUC to solve this problem again.

Data¶

The dataset can be found at:

http://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/default+of+credit+card+clients#

The credit card issuer has gathered information on 30000 customers. The dataset contains information on 25 variables, including demographic factors, credit data, history of payment, and bill statements of credit card customers from April 2005 to September 2005, as well as information on the outcome: did the customer default or not?

There are 25 variables:

ID: ID of each client

LIMIT_BAL: Amount of given credit in NT dollars (includes individual and family/supplementary credit

SEX: Gender (1=male, 2=female)

EDUCATION: (1=graduate school, 2=university, 3=high school, 4=others, 5=unknown, 6=unknown)

MARRIAGE: Marital status (1=married, 2=single, 3=others)

AGE: Age in years

PAY_0: Repayment status in September, 2005 (-1=pay duly, 1=payment delay for one month, 2=payment delay for two months, ... 8=payment delay for eight months, 9=payment delay for nine months and above)
PAY_2: Repayment status in August, 2005 (scale same as above)
PAY_3: Repayment status in July, 2005 (scale same as above)
PAY_4: Repayment status in June, 2005 (scale same as above)
PAY_5: Repayment status in May, 2005 (scale same as above)
PAY_6: Repayment status in April, 2005 (scale same as above)

BILL_AMT1: Amount of bill statement in September, 2005 (NT dollar)
BILL_AMT2: Amount of bill statement in August, 2005 (NT dollar)
BILL_AMT3: Amount of bill statement in July, 2005 (NT dollar)
BILL_AMT4: Amount of bill statement in June, 2005 (NT dollar)
BILL_AMT5: Amount of bill statement in May, 2005 (NT dollar)
BILL_AMT6: Amount of bill statement in April, 2005 (NT dollar)

PAY_AMT1: Amount of previous payment in September, 2005 (NT dollar)
PAY_AMT2: Amount of previous payment in August, 2005 (NT dollar)
PAY_AMT3: Amount of previous payment in July, 2005 (NT dollar)
PAY_AMT4: Amount of previous payment in June, 2005 (NT dollar)
PAY_AMT5: Amount of previous payment in May, 2005 (NT dollar)
PAY_AMT6: Amount of previous payment in April, 2005 (NT dollar)

default.payment.next.month: Default payment (1=yes, 0=no)

Models¶

Since it is a classification problem, we really have lots of choices to use, like the following algorithms:

  • Logistic regression
  • Decision tree
  • Random forest
  • Support Vector Classifications
  • Stocastic Gradient Descend
  • Nearest Neighbours Classifiers
  • Gaussian Process Classification
  • Other ensemble
  • Neural Network Models
  • XGBoost

For here, I want to try the models and to see whether there are some significant improvements.

Based on the knowledge I have so far, I will start with Decision tree.

Decision Tree¶

Decision tree is a easy way to use and can handle both numerical and categorical variables. However, we need to care about the overfitting. To avoid this, we always use random forest.

There are a few parameters to be settle for the classifier, such as the function to determine the quality of a split, or how deep the tree has to be. We will first test it with a random choice of those parameters and then see a better process.

Ok, not bad. 81% based on the random choice but once we change the number of depth and state. It will mess everything up. To avoid that. I use GridSearchCV for helping me to find the ideal combination of parameters.

Before that, I want to overview the three parameters:

  • criterion for here, I use gini which measures how often a randomly chosen element would be incorrectly identified or we can also use entropy which measures the information contained by each attribute
  • max depth is the maximum amount of steps the tree should do
  • max leaf nodes maximum number of nodes
  • min sample split a limit to stop further splitting, useful to avoid overfitting

from sklearn.model_selection import KFold

In [25]:
kf = KFold(n_splits=5,random_state=42,shuffle=True)

fold = []
scr = []

for i,(train_index, test_index) in enumerate(kf.split(df)):
    training = df.iloc[train_index,:]
    valid = df.iloc[test_index,:]
    feats = training[features] #defined above
    label = training['def_pay']
    valid_feats = valid[features]
    valid_label = valid['def_pay']
    classifier.fit(feats,label) #it is the last one we run, the best one
    pred = classifier.predict(valid_feats)
    score = accuracy_score(y_true = valid_label, y_pred = pred)
    fold.append(i+1)
    scr.append(score)
    
#create a small df with the scores
performance = pd.DataFrame({'Score':scr,'Fold':fold})
# let's see what we have with seaborn
sns.set()
sns.relplot(x="Fold", y="Score",kind="line",
            data=performance);
#g = ggplot(performance,aes(x='Fold',y='Score')) + geom_point() + geom_line()

def get_feature_importance(clsf, ftrs):
    imp = clsf.feature_importances_.tolist()
    feat = ftrs
    result = pd.DataFrame({'feat':feat,'score':imp})
    result = result.sort_values(by=['score'],ascending=False)
    return result

In [30]:
# True Positive (TP): we predict a label of 1 (positive), and the true label is 1.
TP = np.sum(np.logical_and(predictions == 1, y_test == 1))
 
# True Negative (TN): we predict a label of 0 (negative), and the true label is 0.
TN = np.sum(np.logical_and(predictions == 0, y_test == 0))
 
# False Positive (FP): we predict a label of 1 (positive), but the true label is 0.
FP = np.sum(np.logical_and(predictions == 1, y_test == 0))
 
# False Negative (FN): we predict a label of 0 (negative), but the true label is 1.
FN = np.sum(np.logical_and(predictions == 0, y_test == 1))
 
print('TP: {}, FP: {}, TN: {}, FN: {}'.format(TP,FP,TN,FN))

TP: 461, FP: 276, TN: 4411, FN: 852

Which is very bad. And let's choose the parameter as same as we pick in the accuracy:

def draw_histograms(df, variables, n_rows, n_cols, n_bins):
    fig=plt.figure()
    for i, var_name in enumerate(variables):
        ax=fig.add_subplot(n_rows,n_cols,i+1)
        df[var_name].hist(bins=n_bins,ax=ax)
        ax.set_title(var_name)
    fig.tight_layout()  # Improves appearance a bit.
    plt.show()

Education and Default¶

And then, let's see how education influence the default rate. For doing that, I create a function to calculate the percentage. It will do the same thing as what we did in Sex and Default but just different method.

In [54]:
def corr_2_cols(Col1, Col2):
    res = df.groupby([Col1, Col2]).size().unstack()
    res['perc'] = (res[res.columns[1]]/(res[res.columns[0]] + res[res.columns[1]]))
    return res

Sampling¶

Since what I did before is imbalanced classes that is why the models perform so bad. Then we need to appropriately sampling the training data and use the best algorithm.

First, I need to decide what kind of features we need to include in the model and split the dataset.

For here, I will use the 3 columns I created before: AgeBin and SEX:MARRIAGE and SEX:AGE

For sampling the dataset,

I upsample the minority class and downsample the majority class and create a syntetic sample

Algorithm¶

For a more effective way to do this, I will try ensambles: combine different classifiers then create a more effective model. I will start, also, decision tree and then test different ensambles.

This includes two parts:

  • baggin ensambles: which reduce the chances of overfitting.
  • boosting ensambles: which improve the the flexibility of simple models.

I will use Random Forest for the baggin ensambles. It can train on a large number of trees and combine them.

For the boosting ensamble, I only know Gradient Tree Boosting, Ada-Boost and XG Boost.

In [76]:

# use Kfold to evaluate the normal training set
kf = KFold(n_splits=5,random_state=42,shuffle=True)

mdl = []
fold = []
scr = []

for i,(train_index, test_index) in enumerate(kf.split(df_train)):
    training = df.iloc[train_index,:]
    valid = df.iloc[test_index,:]
    print(i)
    for clf in clf_list:
        model = clf.__class__.__name__
        feats = training[features] #defined above
        label = training['def_pay']
        valid_feats = valid[features]
        valid_label = valid['def_pay']
        clf.fit(feats,label) 
        pred = clf.predict(valid_feats)
        score = f1_score(y_true = valid_label, y_pred = pred)
        fold.append(i+1)
        scr.append(score)
        mdl.append(model)
        print(model)

# use Kfold to evaluate the upsampled training set
kf = KFold(n_splits=5,random_state=42,shuffle=True)

mdl = []
fold = []
scr = []

for i,(train_index, test_index) in enumerate(kf.split(df_downsampled)):
    training = df.iloc[train_index,:]
    valid = df.iloc[test_index,:]
    print(i)
    for clf in clf_list:
        model = clf.__class__.__name__
        feats = training[features] #defined above
        label = training['def_pay']
        valid_feats = valid[features]
        valid_label = valid['def_pay']
        clf.fit(feats,label) 
        pred = clf.predict(valid_feats)
        score = f1_score(y_true = valid_label, y_pred = pred)
        fold.append(i+1)
        scr.append(score)
        mdl.append(model)
        print(model)

The common result is that the model trained on the normal dataset, which is unbalanced, give a lower f1 score. This also tells me that the a penalized learner (the one with "balanced" options) do not perform as well as one that learned on a balanced sample. The upsampled learners seem to be more promising but, as mentioned, they fall into the overfitting trap more often, so we will see how they perform on the test data.

Testing¶

Finally, let us see how does our model perform. I just run all of them and to see whether it can have significant difference.

Conclusions:¶

To be honest, the results are not good. The problem may happen in the feature engineering part. I literally try every models I learned but still does not perform well.

In this project, I learned how important it is for checking the data unbalancing. And after visualizing the features and understand the relationship between different features.

When I use the models and test the f1 score, I am thinking about that banks do not care about the false negatives if they just want to know the default of the costumers but if the banks are interested in preventing these guys(which I guess they want to). FN will be much more relevant.

To improve this, I searched around and tried to find the best threshold with best f1 score. After that I find some thing interesting is: I evaluated by using the f1-score indicator. Choosing the highest score rarely is my goal. In order to do this, I probably need to create another function to minimize the TP FP TN FN.

However, it could be a very good starting point for me. After this project, the results I got are not wasting my time since I know more about how to build a model and in this process, I understand how important it is and how to preprocess the dataset.

This is a really interesting and useful experience for me and even for the real life. Since now along with the deposit comes up, banks should very care about the costumers who default and how the life influence them. This will definitely help them when they judge how many credit should they give to one person. Remember how Lehman Brothers bankrupt? The root reason is "The subprime mortgage crisis caused the financial products it held to become bad debts" and then do not prevent the bad debts well.

thresholds = []
for thresh in np.arange(0.1, 0.501, 0.01):
    thresh = np.round(thresh, 2)
    res = metrics.f1_score(val_y, (pred_val_y > thresh).astype(int))
    thresholds.append([thresh, res])

thresholds.sort(key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
best_thresh = thresholds[0][0]
print("Best threshold: ", best_thresh)

Metric

XGBoost¶

In [50]:
# Prepare the train and valid datasets
dtrain = xgb.DMatrix(train_df[predictors], train_df[target].values)
dvalid = xgb.DMatrix(val_df[predictors], val_df[target].values)

#What to monitor (in this case, **train** and **valid**)
watchlist = [(dtrain, 'train'), (dvalid, 'valid')]

# Set xgboost parameters
params = {}
params['objective'] = 'binary:logistic'
params['eta'] = 0.039
params['silent'] = True
params['max_depth'] = 2
params['subsample'] = 0.8
params['colsample_bytree'] = 0.9
params['eval_metric'] = 'auc'
params['random_state'] = RANDOM_STATE

Conclusions:¶

  • We started with RandomForrestClassifier, for which we obtained an AUC scode of 0.66. For the RandomForrestClassifier we also experimented with OneHotEncoder, replacing the categorical features with dummified values (introducing one dummy variable for each category). The AUC score did not improved significantly in this case.
  • Next we used an AdaBoostClassifier model, with lower AUC score (0.65).
  • We followed with an CatBoostClassifier model, with lower AUC score (0.66).
  • Then we experimented with a XGBoost model, for which the AUC score obtained was 0.77.
